==English==
===Etymology===
*Latin ''annō Domini'', from ''[[anno|annō]]'', the [[ablative]] of ''[[annus]]'' (''[[year]])'' + ''[[Domini]]'', the [[genitive]] of '''[[Dominus]]''' (''the [[Lord]]'').

===Adverb===
'''annō Domini'''

#{{time}}: in the year of our Lord (often abbreviated [[AD|A.D.]] or [[AD]]). The religion-neutral [[CE]] ([[Common Era]]) is an alternative.
#*'''1620''' — [[s:Mayflower_Compact|Mayflower Compact]]
#*:''In Witness whereof we have hereunto subscribed our names at Cape Cod the eleventh of November, in the Reign of our Sovereign Lord, King James of England, France and Ireland, the eighteenth, and of Scotland the fifty-fourth. '''Anno Domini''', 1620.
#*'''1859''' — [[w:Charles_Dickens|Charles Dickens]], [[s:A_Tale_of_Two_Cities:_Book_the_Second|A Tale of Two Cities]]
#*:''The scene was Mr. Cruncher’s private lodging in Hanging-sword-alley, Whitefriars: the time, half-past seven of the clock on a windy March morning, '''Anno Domini''' seventeen hundred and eighty.''

====Usage====
*The [[w:Chicago Manual of Style|Chicago Manual of Style]] as well as most house styles require placing the [[A.D.]] before the date (e.g., AD 250), although in casual use it is frequently found following the date.

